04715nam a22006975i 9780271066882DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20152015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710668827 a10.1515/97802710668822doi  a(DE-B1597)584529  a(OCoLC)1253312984  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLAN0150002bisacsh04a362.1988/809731 aStormer, Nathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRSA Series in Transdisciplinary Rhetoric. Sign of Pathology :bU.S. Medical Rhetoric on Abortion, 1800s–1960s /cNathan Stormer. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRSA Series in Transdisciplinary Rhetoric ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Struggling Through Life -- tPart 1 -- t1 When Abortion Became a Political-Economic Problem -- t2 Remembering, Forgetting, and the Secrets of Life -- tPart 2 -- t3 “White Man’s Plague”: Anti-Malthusian Memory Work at the Fin de Siècle -- t4 “More Wisdom in Living”: Neo-Malthusian Memory Work at Midcentury -- t5 “The Lesser of Threatened Evils”: Therapeutic Amnesias -- tConclusion: Seeking Immunity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMuch of the political polarization that grips the United States is rooted in the so-called culture wars, and no topic defines this conflict better than the often contentious and sometimes violent debate over abortion rights. In Sign of Pathology, Nathan Stormer reframes our understanding of this conflict by examining the medical literature on abortion from the 1800s to the 1960s. Often framed as an argument over a right to choose versus a right to life, our current understanding of this conflict is as a contest over who has the better position on reproductive biology. Against this view, Sign of Pathology argues that, as it became a medical problem, abortion also became a template, more generally, for struggling with how to live—far exceeding discussions of the merits of providing abortions or how to care for patients. Abortion practices (and all the legal, moral, and ideological entanglements thereof) have rested firmly at the center of debate over many fundamental institutions and concepts—namely, the individual, the family, the state, human rights, and, indeed, the human. Medical rhetoric, then, was decisive in cultivating abortion as a mode of cultural critique, even weaponizing it for discursive conflict on these important subjects, although the goal of the medical practice of abortion has never been to establish this kind of struggle. Stormer argues that the medical discourse of abortion physicians transformed the state of abortion into an indicator that the culture was ill, attacking itself during and through pregnancy in a wrongheaded attempt to cope with reproduction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aAbortionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRhetoric. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aAbortion Rhetoric.  aBiopower Medicine.  aPathology Memory Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271066882?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271066882423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271066882/original  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SS